===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

{{liushu|p}}. Possible interpretations:
* The sepal of a flower; original form of {{och-l|蒂|stem; peduncle}}. {{attn|zh|may need explanation of why this may be unlikely http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_4b41fa86010165ca.html}}
* Tied-up [[firewood]]; original form of {{och-l|禘}}.
* An altar; original form of {{och-l|禘}}.
* An [[asterism]] joining three stars of [[Ursa Major]] with three of [[Ursa Minor]], together with [[Thuban]] and [[Kochab]]. Around 2000 BCE the three top-to-bottom lines would have crossed at the north celestial pole, where the god 帝 dwelt ({{zh-ref|Pankenier, 2004}}).

The character's first attested use is for “God of Heaven”; it was later used as a title for emperors. ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' erroneously interprets the character to be a {{Han compound|丄|朿|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=up; above|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro||*teɣ|God}}; compare {{cog|bo|tr=the|t=celestial gods of the Bon religion}}, {{cog|kac|tr=mə³¹-tai³³|t=god of the sky}}, {{cog|tbq-bdg-pro|*mɯ-Dai⁴||spirit; god}} ({{zh-ref|Coblin, 1986}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Sagart, 2011}}). Cognate with {{och-l|禘|a kind of sacrifice}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} derives it from a root {{m|und|*tek||to be master over; to rule over}}, whence also {{och-l|適|tr=*ᵃtek|to rule; to control}}, {{och-l|嫡|tr=*ᵃtek|son of principal wife}}.

